<section xml:id="sec-examples-of-linear-transformations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Examples</title>

  <p>
    We discuss two classes of linear transformations in this section.
  </p>

  <p>
<term>Rotation:</term> An important example of a linear transformation is rotation. Given an angle <m>\theta</m> (which for the purposes
of our diagrams we will think of as an angle between 0 and <m>\pi/2</m>, but this all works for any angle), we define the 
function <m>R_\theta\colon \R^2\to\R^2</m> by setting <m>R_\theta(\vect{u})</m>$ to be the result of rotating 
<m>\vect{u}</m> anticlockwise by angle <m>\theta</m>. This function is linear. We illustrate the additivity 
(property 1 of being linear) in <xref ref="fig-first-pic-of-rotation"/>, and we will leave drawing a diagram for 
scaling as an exercise.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="fig-first-pic-of-rotation">
<caption>This figure illustrates that rotation is additive (one half of being linear): adding <m>\vect{u}</m>
  and <m>\vect{v}</m> and then rotating to get <m>R_\theta(\vect{u}+\vect{v})</m> gives the same vector as rotating
  first to get <m>R_\theta(\vect{u})</m> and <m>R_\theta(\vect{v})</m>, and then adding to get
  <m>R_\theta(\vect{u})+R_\theta(\vect{v})</m>.
</caption>
